In January, I went to Lithuania on business trip.
It's shameful to say, but I had very limited knowledge of Lithuania then.
Even the name of the capital Vilnius, I couldn't spell it.
Almost only thing I knew well was that a Japanese diplomat Chiune Sugihara who served as acting consul in Kaunas.
He risked his carrier, but took the the action to protect every individual indispensable life.
This story was famous in Japan and there is even a movie about it.
So I had wanted to ask some Lithuanians if they knew something about Sugihara or Japan since I came to Lithuania.
I couldn't believe the answers I could get because they were more than I had expected.
Of course, she knew Sugihara and heard of the whole story.
Thinking of the Lithuanian situation where many highly educated master graduates have to work as clerk in apparel shop or in fast food chain shops, it could be taken granted for that a Lithuania working at one of the Japanese leading companies had a profound knowledge of history.
But what if around 20 years guys who were not interested in school subjects could know Sugihara and tell me the history eloquently.
Maybe around thirty past four o'clock.
I had to stay up and work all night to fulfill the all tasks by the deadline.
By four o'clock I managed to have all tasks done and the only things left was to print out 50 each of 5 different documents and bring them to the headquarter by taxi.
By 20 minutes before the deadline all copies was done, but 50 more copies of an additional document sent from Estonia suddenly needed bringing to the headquarter together with the other documents.
It takes 8 minutes by taxi from my workplace to the headquarter.
So I thought then there were still 20 minutes left and I could make it.
The extra copies were done as well 5 minutes after then, I rushed to the entry where a taxi was supposed to wait for me.
When I look back on it now, it still makes my heart be beating.
If I could have called another taxi, I was told to have waited for it for 15 minutes.
It could never make it by my deadline.
That's why I thought I had to catch a taxi driving on the street along my workplace, but there was dark outside at twenty five past four o'clock in the morning and I didn't see something move.
For only a moment I could fortunately see a faint light in the darkness in a parking area of supermarket.
I was acting in instinct.
There was only 5 minutes left until deadline, so I didn't have any choice but run to catch the possibility still left.
The faint light was actually a car light and it was almost teenagers those who were eating early breakfast in the car.
I explained to them that I had to bring my documents to headquarter as soon as possible and asked if they could drive me there.
They were first confused, but I was not sure if they felt my sense of crisis and they accepted my offer soon after that.
What made me most surprised was that even these guys knew Sugihara and told me that almost all Lithuanians get to know him before you start to learn him and the story in a history class.
